This PR adds `Object::emits_signal` to check if `emit_signal` will actually emit a signal. This came up while working on #10655, but I imagine this situation might crop up in other places as well. So this is one idea to solve it.

Details:

In `Polygon2D::set_polygon`, the calculation of the item rect is currently deferred using `rect_cache_dirty`:

```
void Polygon2D::set_polygon(const PoolVector<Vector2> &p_polygon) {
	polygon = p_polygon;
	rect_cache_dirty = true;
	update();
}
```

Adding a signal on item rect changes might look like this:

```
void Polygon2D::set_polygon(const PoolVector<Vector2> &p_polygon) {
	polygon = p_polygon;
	rect_cache_dirty = true;
	update();
	emit_signal("item_rect_changed"); // note: rect might not have changed
}
```

However, not each polygon change changes the item rect. In order to emit the signal only on actual changes, we need to break deferment:

```
void Polygon2D::set_polygon(const PoolVector<Vector2> &p_polygon) {
	const Rect2 old_rect = get_item_rect(); // breaks deferment

	polygon = p_polygon;
	rect_cache_dirty = true;
	update();

	const Rect2 new_rect = get_item_rect(); // breaks deferment
	if (new_rect != old_rect)
		emit_signal(item_rect_changed);
}
```

The problem with the code above is that this now completely breaks deferment, even if no actual signal is attached (i.e. `emit_signal` is a noop).

In order to keep the deferment and only break it when necessary we need a way to check if a signal is attached, which this PR's `emits_signal` is about:

```
void Polygon2D::set_polygon(const PoolVector<Vector2> &p_polygon) {

	if (emits_signal("item_rect_changed")) {
		const Rect2 old_rect = get_item_rect();

		polygon = p_polygon;
		rect_cache_dirty = true;
		update();

		const Rect2 new_rect = get_item_rect();
		if (new_rect != old_rect)
			emit_signal("item_rect_changed");
	} else {
		polygon = p_polygon;
		rect_cache_dirty = true;
		update();
	}
}
```
